{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:50:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:50:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20771"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13646"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78632"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11746"},{"type":"tags","id":"12623"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32844"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHuman fibroblasts exposed to ultraviolet radiation show formation of pyrimidine dimers in their DNA. Following exposure, most cells temporarily stop dividing, while some undergo programmed cell death.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary cellular response pathway activated by DNA damage in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Necroptosis signalling cascade","Unfolded protein response","Induction of autophagy","p53-mediated cell cycle arrest","Activation of heat shock proteins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ep53-mediated cell cycle arrest\u003C/strong\u003E. When DNA damage occurs (such as pyrimidine dimers caused by ultraviolet radiation), p53 is activated and serves as the master regulator of the cellular response. p53 initially arrests cells in the G1 phase of the cell cycle, preventing them from dividing with damaged DNA. This provides time for DNA repair mechanisms to correct the damage. If repair is successful, cells can resume normal cycling. However, if the damage is too extensive to be repaired, p53 triggers apoptosis via the mitochondrial pathway, explaining why a subset of cells in the experiment underwent programmed cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of heat shock proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Heat shock proteins are primarily involved in protein folding and are activated in response to protein denaturation during various stresses, but they are not the primary response to DNA damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduction of autophagy\u003C/strong\u003E - While autophagy can be triggered by various cellular stresses, it is not the primary response pathway to DNA damage. Autophagy involves the degradation of cellular components in lysosomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecroptosis signalling cascade\u003C/strong\u003E - Necroptosis is a form of programmed necrotic cell death that is distinct from apoptosis and is not typically the primary response to DNA damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfolded protein response\u003C/strong\u003E - This is activated in response to accumulation of unfolded or misfolded proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum, not in response to DNA damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe p53 pathway is crucial for preventing the propagation of cells with damaged DNA that could lead to malignant transformation. Mutations in p53 that interfere with its ability to arrest cell cycling or induce apoptosis are associated with numerous cancers, highlighting its importance as a tumour suppressor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["DNA damage activates p53, which arrests cells in G1 phase and initiates DNA repair mechanisms.","When DNA repair fails, p53 triggers apoptosis via the mitochondrial pathway to prevent survival of cells with potentially oncogenic mutations.","DNA damage can result from radiation, chemotherapeutic drugs, reactive oxygen species, or spontaneous deamination of cytosine to uracil during aging.","Mutations in p53 that impair its ability to arrest cell cycling or induce apoptosis are associated with numerous cancers."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 2; page 51."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78632"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78632"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T01:08:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T01:12:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13646"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury